1️⃣ Possible Issues with Logger in Tests

Since you are using Spring Boot’s @Bean method for Logger, here’s what could be happening:
	1.	The logger is null inside the controller during the test → If the bean is not injected correctly.
	2.	Mockito doesn’t mock logger.info(...) properly → If Spring still tries to call the real logger instead of the mock.
	3.	Spring tries to create the Logger bean but fails in the test environment.

⸻

2️⃣ Fix: Ensure Logger Is Properly Mocked

In your JUnit test, add this to correctly mock the logger:

@WebMvcTest(AddressController.class)
class AddressControllerTest {

    @Autowired
    private MockMvc mockMvc;

    @MockBean
    private Logger logger; // ✅ Ensures logger is mocked in tests

    @MockBean
    private AddressService addressService;

    @Test
    void testInvalidRequest_ReturnsBadRequest() throws Exception {
        when(addressService.searchAddress(any(), anyMap()))
            .thenThrow(new CustomValidationException("Agent Id must be provided as input"));

        mockMvc.perform(post("/common/address/search")
                .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON)
                .content("{}") // Invalid request
                .accept(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON))
                .andExpect(status().isBadRequest());

        verify(logger, atLeastOnce()).info(anyString()); // ✅ Verifies logging was called
    }
}

🚀 Why This Works?
	•	Ensures the logger is injected correctly in tests (@MockBean private Logger logger;).
	•	Prevents NullPointerException when calling logger.info(...) in the controller.
	•	Verifies if logging is the issue (verify(logger, atLeastOnce()).info(anyString());).

