3️⃣ Debugging Steps to Confirm If Logger Is the Issue

If you’re still getting 500 Internal Server Error, add a debugging print statement inside the controller:

@PostMapping("/search")
public ResponseEntity<List<AddressDTO>> searchAddress(@Valid @RequestBody AddressSearchConditionsDTO searchConditions) {
    System.out.println("Inside Controller - Before Logging");
    logger.info("Received request: {}", searchConditions);
    System.out.println("Inside Controller - After Logging");

    List<AddressDTO> results = addressService.searchAddress(searchConditions, new HashMap<>());
    return ResponseEntity.ok(results);
}

Then, run the test and check logs:
	•	If “Inside Controller - Before Logging” appears but “After Logging” does not, the issue is with the logger.
	•	If both messages appear, but you still get 500, the issue is somewhere else.

⸻

4️⃣ If Logger Is Causing 500, Try a Workaround

If the logger is causing the issue, try disabling logging in tests:

✅ Option 1: Disable Logger Bean Injection in Tests

@TestConfiguration
static class TestConfig {
    @Bean
    public Logger logger() {
        return mock(Logger.class); // ✅ Mocks logger as a Spring bean
    }
}

🚀 Why?
	•	Ensures that even in Spring Boot tests, the logger is mocked properly.

✅ Option 2: Remove Logger in Tests Using @TestPropertySource

If you don’t need logging in tests, disable it in application-test.properties:

logging.level.org.springframework.web=ERROR

🚀 Why?
	•	Prevents logs from causing unwanted issues in tests.

